@using BrandSheet.Helpers;
<link rel="stylesheet" href="../Styles/brandsheet.css" />
@* Font Switcher  *@
@*
    Apply any additonal fonts in the same way below.
    - Reference the google font or a local file
    -
*@
<div data-class="section" data-id="fontswitcher">
    <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Lato:400,700|Open+Sans:400,600,700|Roboto:400,500,700|Rubik:400,500,700" rel="stylesheet" defer />
    <script type="text/javascript">
        $("div[data-id='fontswitcher']").on("click", "a", function (e) {
            e.preventDefault();
            $("body").prop("class", $(this).prop("class"));
        });
    </script>
    <style type="text/css">
        .roboto *, a.roboto {
            font-family: Roboto !important;
        }

        .lato *, a.lato {
            font-family: Lato !important;
        }

        .rubik *, a.rubik {
            font-family: Rubik !important;
        }

        .opensans *, a.opensans {
            font-family: 'Open Sans' !important;
        }
    </style>
    <span data-class="sectiontitle">Font Switcher</span>
    <a href="#" data-class="default" class="">Default</a>
    <a href="#" class="roboto">Roboto</a>
    <a href="#" class="lato">Lato</a>
    <a href="#" class="rubik">Rubik</a>
    <a href="#" class="opensans">Open Sans</a>
</div>
@* End Font Switcher  *@

<div data-class="section">
    <span data-class="sectiontitle">Headings</span>
    <div data-class="ruleset">
        <span data-class="rule">All page titles to use capital letters for each word, e.g. "Page Template"</span>
    </div>
    <h1>Heading 1</h1>
    <h2>Heading 2</h2>
    <h3>Heading 3</h3>
</div>
<div data-class="section">
    <span data-class="sectiontitle">Paragraphs</span>
    <p>Before cherries, shrines were only <i>witnesses</i>. An input is a sweatshirt's story. The lumber of a luttuce becomes a fecund black. A screeching ladybug's minister comes with it the thought that the awnless drizzle is a tent.</p>
    <p>The literature would have us believe that an <a href="#">untailed</a> queen is not but a bee. The edward is a bolt. Unfortunately, that is wrong; on the contrary, we can assume that any instance of a period can be construed as a condemned mice. The downtowns could be said to resemble wholesale differences.</p>
    <p>A doll of the kayak is <b>assumed</b> to be a pursued elbow. Authors often misinterpret the rate as a zincy slash, when in actuality it feels more like a jannock fahrenheit. The bowl is an elephant. This could be, or perhaps before augusts, beans were only pikes.</p>
</div>
<div data-class="section">
    <span data-class="sectiontitle">Inputs</span>
